<subSubSection pageId="76" pageNumber="77" type="key">
<keyStep pageId="76" pageNumber="77">
<paragraph blockId="76.[151,1436,1578,1983]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">
<keyLead pageId="76" pageNumber="77">
1a. Rostral circular in dorsal view and not strongly projecting; short nasal suture arising from the rostral; dorsum light red-brown, pigment confined to posterior half of each scale 
<taxonomicName box="[852,992,1613,1636]" class="Reptilia" family="Typhlopidae" genus="Megatyphlops" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="anomalus">
<emphasis box="[852,992,1613,1636]" italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">M. anomalus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="76.[151,1436,1578,1983]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">
<keyLead pageId="76" pageNumber="77">1b. Rostral unguiform, oval or cuneiform in dorsal view, strongly projecting; long nasal suture arising from first or second supralabial; dorsum lineolate, blotched, mottled or uniform black or grey-brown ............................................ 2</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="76" pageNumber="77">
<paragraph blockId="76.[151,1436,1578,1983]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">
<keyLead pageId="76" pageNumber="77">
2a. Rostral unguiform in dorsal view; midbody scale rows usually 34–44; dorsum mottled with black or entirely black 
<emphasis box="[220,1436,1752,1775]" italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">
................................................................................................................................................................. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mcdiarmid, Campbell &amp; Toure" authorityYear="1999" box="[1298,1436,1752,1775]" class="Reptilia" family="Typhlopidae" genus="Rhinotyphlops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="schlegelii">M. schlegelii</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="76.[151,1436,1578,1983]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">
<keyLead pageId="76" pageNumber="77">2b. Rostral oval or cuneiform in dorsal view; midbody scale rows usually 30–36; dorsum lineolate, blotched with black or uniform grey-brown ...................................................................................................................................... 3</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="76" pageNumber="77">
<paragraph blockId="76.[151,1436,1578,1983]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">
<keyLead pageId="76" pageNumber="77">
3a. Rostral oval in dorsal view, convex in profile; rostral length/width ratio usually less than 1.25; lineolate or blotched, some large adults uniform grey-brown ..................................................................................... 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Broadley &amp; Wallach" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Broadley &amp; Wallach" baseAuthorityYear="2009" box="[1308,1436,1890,1913]" class="Reptilia" family="Typhlopidae" genus="Megatyphlops" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="mucruso">
<emphasis box="[1308,1436,1890,1913]" italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">M. mucruso</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="76.[151,1436,1578,1983]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">
<keyLead pageId="76" pageNumber="77">
3b. Rostral cuneiform in dorsal view, depressed in profile; rostral length/width ratio usually more than 1.25; juveniles lineolate, adults uniform grey-brown 
<emphasis box="[606,1429,1960,1983]" italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">
............................................................................................................ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Broadley &amp; Wallach" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Broadley &amp; Wallach" baseAuthorityYear="2009" box="[1329,1429,1960,1983]" class="Reptilia" family="Typhlopidae" genus="Megatyphlops" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brevis">M. brevis</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
